// Man page for scan
manScan="SCAN(1)                          X Shell Manual                          SCAN(1)

<b>NAME</b>
    scan - Vulnerability scanner and exploit framework
<b>SYNOPSIS</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -l</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -lp</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -n</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -r</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -d</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -nf</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -nd</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -nfd</b>
    <b>scan</b><b> -a</b> [<b>-w</b> CRITERIA] [<b>-s</b> START_IP] [<b>-e</b> END_IP]
    <b>scan</b><b> -p</b> IP PORT|LIBRARY
    <b>scan</b><b> -pd</b> PATH
    <b>scan</b> IP|DOMAIN
    <b>scan</b> LAN_IP
    <b>scan</b><b> --n</b> [<b>-r</b> ROUTER_IP] LIBRARY OBJECT [EXTRA]
    <b>scan</b><b> --l</b> LIBRARY INDEX [EXTRA]
    <b>scan</b><b> --e</b> TYPE [<b>-u</b> USER] [EXTRA]
    <b>scan</b><b> --c</b> IP LIBRARY OBJECT [EXTRA]
    <b>scan</b><b> -b</b> <b>-p</b> PUBLIC_IP <b>-l</b> LAN_IP
    <b>scan</b><b> --b</b> <b>-p</b> PUBLIC_IP <b>-l</b> LAN_IP [CMD [then CMD ...]]
    <b>scan</b><b> --s</b> LAN_IP [<b>-S</b>] [CMD [then CMD ...]]
    <b>scan</b><b> --s</b> IP LIBRARY OBJECT [<b>--router</b>] [<b>-S</b>] [CMD [then CMD ...]]
<b>DESCRIPTION</b>
    Comprehensive vulnerability scanner and exploit framework. Scans local
    host, local networks, and remote targets for security weaknesses.
    Provides automated exploitation and post-exploitation capabilities.
    Supports custom library scanning with smart flag syntax.

    Port shortcuts: router:0, ssh:22, ftp:21, http:80, chat:6667,
    rshell:1222, repo:1542, cam:37777, sql:3306, smtp:25

    Object types and exploits:
    s=shell access
    c=computer object
    f=file object
    l=lan bounce
    i=internal lan bounce
    d=disable firewall
    p=change root password
    w=change user password
<b>OPTIONS</b>
    <b>-l</b>
    Scan and attack localhost

    <b>-lp</b>
    Scan localhost including 0day exploits

    <b>-n</b>
    Scan local network for targets interactively

    IP|DOMAIN
    Scan and exploit a remote public IP or domain

    <b>LAN_IP</b>
    Directly scan a LAN IP address (e.g. 192.168.1.5)
    Automatically finds the correct parent router, lists open ports,
    shows firewall rules if present, and launches the exploit menu
    Pipe: echo 192.168.1.5 | scan  (pipe LAN IP)

    <b>-r</b>
    Find random network to exploit

    <b>-d</b>
    Disable all network firewalls

    <b>-nf</b>
    Show local network firewalls

    <b>-nd</b>
    Attempt to disable network firewalls

    <b>-nfd</b>
    Show and disable network firewalls

    <b>-a</b> [<b>-w</b> CRITERIA] [<b>-s</b> START_IP] [<b>-e</b> END_IP]
    Mass IP scan with optional filtering
    Without params scans 1.0.0.0 to 255.255.255.255
    Results saved to text files in current directory

    <b>-p</b> IP PORT|LIBRARY
    Attack partial object by IP and port or library
    Use port shortcuts or library path
    Pipe: echo IP PORT | scan -p  (pipe IP and port)

    <b>-pd</b> PATH
    Scan library folder for partial objects
    Insert found objects into database
    Recommended path is /lib
    Pipe: echo /lib | scan -pd  (pipe directory path)

    <b>--n</b> LIBRARY OBJECT [EXTRA]
    Smart scan local network by library
    LIBRARY: partial name supported (apt for aptclient.so)
    OBJECT: target type (s|c|f|l|i|d|p|w)
    EXTRA: optional parameters to pass

    <b>--l</b> LIBRARY INDEX [EXTRA]
    Custom local scan with specific exploit index
    Requires library name and exploit number
    Pass extra parameters if needed

    <b>--e</b> TYPE [<b>-u</b> USER] [EXTRA]
    Search all libraries for exploit by target type
    Scans local network for matching exploits
    Automatically prioritizes root -> user -> guest
    TYPE: target object (shell|computer|file|lan|bounce...)
    <b>-u</b> USER: filter by privilege (root|user|guest)
    EXTRA: additional params (LAN address for bounce exploits)

    <b>--c</b> IP LIBRARY OBJECT [EXTRA]
    Custom public IP scan and exploit
    Use <b>-r</b> for random IP or specify target
    Requires library, object type, optional params
    LIBRARY supports partial names and <b>find</b> for auto-selection
    OBJECT supports short codes (s|c|f|l|i|d|p|w) and friendly names
    (shell|computer|file|lan|bounce|rootpass|userpass)
    For shell auto-selection, non-router shells are preferred over router shells
    Use <b>--router</b> to require router-shell-only selection
    <b>--router</b> may be placed anywhere after <b>--c</b>

    <b>-b -p</b> PUBLIC_IP <b>-l</b> LAN_IP
    Automated bounce attack to obtain root computer
    Connects to router via public IP, pivots to LAN
    Escalates privileges and returns root computer object
    Wipes logs for stealth operation
    Requires: config -v (vulnerable lib) and -x (lib index) must be set

    <b>--b -p</b> PUBLIC_IP <b>-l</b> LAN_IP [CMD [then CMD ...]]
    Same as -b but optionally runs commands then exits
    With trailing commands: headless computer that auto-exits after each cmd
    Without trailing commands: drops into interactive computer session
    Use <b>then</b> to chain multiple commands (not && or ; — those are split by the shell)
    Requires: config -v (vulnerable lib) and -x (lib index) must be set

    <b>--s</b> LAN_IP [<b>-S</b>] [CMD [then CMD ...]]
    <b>--s</b> IP LIBRARY OBJECT [<b>--router</b>] [<b>-S</b>] [CMD [then CMD ...]]
    Like --c but gets a shell and optionally runs commands then exits
    If LAN_IP is given (detected via is_lan_ip), LIBRARY and OBJECT are
    not required — scans all ports on the device and selects the best
    available shell (root -> user -> guest)
    LIBRARY supports partial names and <b>find</b> for auto-selection
    OBJECT: target type (s = shell)
    <b>--router</b>: require router-shell-only selection
    <b>-S</b>: escalate to root via su after getting shell
    With trailing commands: headless shell that auto-exits after each cmd
    Without trailing commands: drops into interactive shell session
    Use <b>then</b> to chain multiple commands (not && or ; — split by the shell)
<b>SCRIPTING FLAGS</b>
    All <b>--</b> flags are bash-aware scripting flags. They work from the CLI as well
    as inside <b>run</b> scripts. Each <b>--</b> flag resets <b>$scan_ok</b> and <b>$hold</b> before
    running, then sets them based on the result.

    <b>$scan_ok</b>
    Set to <b>true</b> if the operation succeeded, <b>false</b> if it failed.
    Always check <b>$scan_ok</b> after a <b>--</b> flag call before using the result.
    Errors are printed but do not stop the script — the script continues
    and <b>$scan_ok</b> tells you whether to proceed.

    <b>$hold</b>
    Set to the resulting computer (<b>--b</b>) or shell (<b>--s</b>) object when no
    trailing commands are given and the operation succeeds.
    Null when trailing commands are given, the scan failed, or the flag
    does not produce a session object (<b>--n</b>, <b>--l</b>, <b>--c</b>, <b>--e</b>).
    Use <b>_hold CMD [ARGS...]</b> to dispatch commands to the held session.
    Use <b>_hold home</b> or <b>_hold exit</b> to close the session and clear <b>$hold</b>.
    Use <b>_setvar(name, _hold)</b> to name the object for later use with <b>OBJ(name)</b>.

    Flags and what they return:
      <b>--b</b>  Bounce attack via LAN      — sets $hold to computer object
      <b>--s</b>  Remote shell exploit       — sets $hold to shell object
      <b>--c</b>  Custom remote exploit      — sets $scan_ok (no $hold)
      <b>--l</b>  Custom local exploit       — sets $scan_ok (no $hold)
      <b>--n</b>  LAN custom exploit         — sets $scan_ok (no $hold)
      <b>--e</b>  Exploit-file scan          — sets $scan_ok (no $hold)

    Example (bash script):
      scan --b -p $1 -l $2
      if $scan_ok then
        _hold ls
        _hold cat /etc/passwd
        _hold home
      else
        _print red(Bounce failed)
      endif

    Example (CLI — same flags work interactively):
      <b>scan --s 31.198.119.192 find shell --router</b>
      Drops into an interactive shell session

    See <b>run</b> for full scripting reference including <b>_hold</b>, <b>_setvar</b>, and <b>OBJ()</b>.
<b>EXAMPLE:</b>
    <color=#e4ff34># Basic Scanning</color>
    <b>scan -l</b>
    Scan and attack localhost

    <b>scan -lp</b>
    Localhost with 0day exploits

    <b>scan -n</b>
    Scan local network

    <color=#e4ff34># Remote Targeting</color>
    <b>scan target.com</b>
    Attack remote host

    <b>scan -r</b>
    Find random target

    <color=#e4ff34># LAN Targeting</color>
    <b>scan 192.168.1.5</b>
    Directly attack a LAN device by IP
    Scans all open ports, shows firewall rules, launches exploit menu

    <b>scan 192.168.4.1</b>
    Directly attack a LAN sub-router
    Automatically includes kernel port (port 0) alongside HTTP port

    <color=#e4ff34># Partial Object Attacks</color>
    <b>scan -p target.host 0</b>
    Attack router port

    <b>scan -p target.host 22</b>
    Attack SSH service

    <b>scan -p /lib/init.so</b>
    Attack with specific library

    <color=#e4ff34># Smart Scanning</color>
    <b>scan --n http s</b>
    Find shell via HTTP on LAN

    <b>scan --l apt 6 router.local</b>
    Custom local exploit with router param

    <b>scan --c target.host router l gateway.local</b>
    Remote LAN bounce via router

    <b>scan --c target.host find s</b>
    Auto-find and execute best shell exploit on target

    <b>scan --c target.host find shell</b>
    Same as above using friendly object name

    <b>scan --c target.host find shell --router</b>
    Require router shell selection only (port 0)

    <b>scan --c --router target.host find shell</b>
    Same as above with flag-first ordering

    <color=#e4ff34># Firewall Management</color>
    <b>scan -nf</b>
    Show network firewalls

    <b>scan -nd</b>
    Disable network firewalls

    <b>scan -d</b>
    Disable all firewalls

    <color=#e4ff34># Mass Scanning</color>
    <b>scan -a -w Neurobox -s 1.196.1.169 -e 1.196.255.169</b>
    Scan IP range for Neurobox machines

    <b>scan -pd /lib</b>
    Index all library exploits

    <b>scan -pd /home/user/libs</b>
    Index custom library folder

    <color=#e4ff34># Pipe Input</color>
    <b>echo 192.168.1.5 | scan</b>
    Pipe a LAN IP directly into scan

    <b>echo 10.0.0.1 22 | scan -p</b>
    Pipe IP and port to partial object scanner

    <b>echo /lib | scan -pd</b>
    Pipe a directory path to partial object scanner

    <color=#e4ff34># Bounce Attack</color>
    <b>scan -b -p 104.203.108.34 -l 192.168.11.11</b>
    Automated bounce via router to LAN computer

    <b>scan --b -p 104.203.108.34 -l 192.168.11.11 list -sB</b>
    Execute list on target then auto-exit

    <b>scan --b -p 104.203.108.34 -l 192.168.11.11 list -sB then ls</b>
    Chain multiple commands then auto-exit (use <b>then</b>, not && or ;)

    <b>echo 104.203.108.34 192.168.11.11 | scan --b list -sB</b>
    Same via pipe

    <color=#e4ff34># Shell Bounce (--s)</color>
    <b>scan --s 31.198.119.192 find shell --router</b>
    Get interactive shell on target via best router exploit

    <b>scan --s 31.198.119.192 find shell --router -S</b>
    Same but escalate to root

    <b>scan --s 31.198.119.192 find shell --router ls</b>
    Run ls on target then return (no interactive shell)

    <b>scan --s 31.198.119.192 http s -S list -sB then ps</b>
    Root shell, run two commands then return

    <b>echo 31.198.119.192 http s | scan --s -S ls</b>
    Pipe IP, lib, type — escalate and run ls
<b>SEE ALSO</b>
    <b>open</b>, <b>exp</b>, <b>sys</b>"